WEBVTT

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:06.800
So, in 2022, Joe Chang had a really powerful statement where he said,

00:00:06.800 --> 00:00:11.040
R is the best language for Shiny, and I will die on this hill.

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:17.280
And he was quick to mention that Dan Callahan in PyCon 2018

00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:19.520
said Python is the second best language for anything.

00:00:20.480 --> 00:00:24.080
And my name is Barret Schloerke, and I'm on the Shiny team,

00:00:24.080 --> 00:00:28.160
and I kind of believe right now my job is to kind of change their minds.

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:30.080
So, yeah.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:36.639
Before we get more into data frames and how they're used within Shiny,

00:00:36.639 --> 00:00:40.080
I want to talk about where we've been so we can kind of see,

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:43.759
you know, where we're going or kind of how we're going to repeat history just a little bit.

00:00:45.439 --> 00:00:50.160
In 2012, Shiny was created at the end of the year,

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:54.959
and about eight months later, they added support for Render Data Table.

00:00:55.919 --> 00:00:57.279
And it was neat.

00:00:57.279 --> 00:01:00.799
Like, you need to add in those components, you know, as they're coming in.

00:01:02.320 --> 00:01:07.199
About three years later, that data frame support was offloaded into the DT package.

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:12.000
We could then leverage DataTables.js and all of its glory

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:15.919
so that we're using other people's experience to our advantage.

00:01:18.080 --> 00:01:19.599
Let's take a look at what DT can do.

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:23.599
With the table on the left, you can select some rows.

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:25.839
You can have pagination.

00:01:25.839 --> 00:01:32.160
You know, this was an amazing advancement, given the initial early days of Shiny.

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:34.480
Search bar at the top.

00:01:35.599 --> 00:01:39.839
And in the spirit of the Olympics that are going on, I'm going to change my ratings.

00:01:39.839 --> 00:01:44.559
There's no representation of anyone else, but my ratings into Olympic gold medals.

00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:47.680
So, filtering is possible.

00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:51.919
It's just a simple regex, or, you know, a small matching.

00:01:53.199 --> 00:01:54.160
You can style.

00:01:54.160 --> 00:01:56.400
It's a little bit of an uphill battle, but it's possible.

00:01:57.360 --> 00:01:59.519
The API has a lot of options.

00:01:59.519 --> 00:02:02.959
It's kind of a little overwhelming for me, you know, in today's world.

00:02:02.959 --> 00:02:05.760
So, I'm, you know, we'll kind of back down to a bronze.

00:02:06.559 --> 00:02:10.240
Speed is not the best when we get into the 100,000, in my experience.

00:02:11.199 --> 00:02:12.800
But it is there and available.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:15.199
But the editing is pretty good.

00:02:15.279 --> 00:02:19.520
You're very aware that you're able to edit, or what can be edited.

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:24.720
And how it sends back values to Shiny is a little wonky for me,

00:02:24.720 --> 00:02:27.279
but it sends you all the information that it can.

00:02:30.479 --> 00:02:35.039
About one month later, our Hanson table came out.

00:02:35.039 --> 00:02:36.160
Hands-on table.

00:02:36.160 --> 00:02:39.039
I never know the name, but I always see it as hands-on.

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:42.240
It had a really beautiful editing experience.

00:02:42.240 --> 00:02:47.600
It came to the, like, towards Shiny using hands-on table JS.

00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:50.800
And that is a spreadsheet first approach.

00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:54.000
So, we want editing to be the first experience that you have.

00:02:54.639 --> 00:02:56.399
And it does a really, really good job.

00:02:56.399 --> 00:02:57.360
It's very impressive.

00:02:57.360 --> 00:03:00.479
So, like, booleans are done as checkboxes.

00:03:00.479 --> 00:03:01.839
There is a select box.

00:03:01.839 --> 00:03:04.639
You can have your typed text text.

00:03:04.639 --> 00:03:06.080
You can have your text text.

00:03:06.399 --> 00:03:09.360
You can have your typed text section.

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:11.119
Even dates are done with a date picker.

00:03:12.160 --> 00:03:14.160
It's very, very pretty in how it was done.

00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:19.279
Unfortunately, there is no filtering with the setup.

00:03:19.279 --> 00:03:21.600
So, you have to do that on the outside yourself.

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:23.440
But you could always just redraw the table.

00:03:25.119 --> 00:03:26.399
Styling is possible.

00:03:26.399 --> 00:03:27.759
The API is a little bit better.

00:03:27.759 --> 00:03:30.000
We're starting to separate it just a little bit.

00:03:31.279 --> 00:03:34.800
But the speed, when it also got quite large with that HTML widget,

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:36.960
it would flicker just a little bit.

00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:40.320
And you didn't quite, you may catch it in that, like, special moment.

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:43.759
But the editing experience, top-notch.

00:03:44.399 --> 00:03:45.600
It's very, very elegant.

00:03:49.520 --> 00:03:50.639
It took a little five-year gap.

00:03:51.199 --> 00:03:52.559
You know, things improved on their own.

00:03:54.160 --> 00:03:56.240
And Reactable came out in 2020.

00:03:57.440 --> 00:04:03.119
And when this package came out, I remember the, by Greg Lynn,

00:04:03.119 --> 00:04:09.119
and I remember the speed at to which this data table would be rendered.

00:04:09.119 --> 00:04:11.679
It was, even just with a simple example here,

00:04:11.679 --> 00:04:14.800
where we say Reactable of the iris dataset on the website,

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:20.640
the GIF that's playing here doesn't show you the print speed and the scroll speed,

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:22.480
the effectiveness of what Reactable does.

00:04:23.200 --> 00:04:24.959
And it was really, really impressive.

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:27.359
It used virtual DOM.

00:04:27.359 --> 00:04:30.320
So, as you scale out this data frame,

00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:33.200
we may only be having 100 rows in the DOM.

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:35.040
And then that makes it really, really fast,

00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:37.679
even though you may have 100,000 in your data.

00:04:38.720 --> 00:04:41.200
So, the browser is not overloaded and thinking too hard.

00:04:42.799 --> 00:04:44.640
And if you put in the effort,

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:48.000
you can get really gorgeous tables in how it's done.

00:04:48.799 --> 00:04:50.399
A lot of custom work will go in.

00:04:50.399 --> 00:04:52.640
So, what you put in is definitely what you'll get out.

00:04:52.640 --> 00:04:56.720
But, like, having a table that can do this and still be interactive

00:04:56.720 --> 00:04:58.239
is really, really impressive.

00:05:01.200 --> 00:05:02.720
So, there is filtering.

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:03.839
It's just for the column.

00:05:05.679 --> 00:05:08.160
Styling is still a little off

00:05:08.160 --> 00:05:11.200
because we're trying to push the computation to the browser.

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:15.839
But that's faster because you don't need to have the server control that.

00:05:17.119 --> 00:05:21.679
The API is really good at providing all the different options.

00:05:21.679 --> 00:05:25.519
And it is separated a little bit to not overload the user at one point.

00:05:25.519 --> 00:05:29.600
But it is not to the point of another package,

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:31.519
which we'll get to next.

00:05:32.079 --> 00:05:33.600
And the speed is amazing.

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:40.320
But this was built for the as a output towards the end.

00:05:40.320 --> 00:05:41.679
So, it doesn't have editing.

00:05:42.320 --> 00:05:45.839
So, we're kind of starting to kind of pick and choose

00:05:45.839 --> 00:05:47.359
which strategies we want to go with.

00:05:49.119 --> 00:05:51.760
But I do want to give a bonus medal of examples.

00:05:52.559 --> 00:06:01.040
And Reactable on its getting started article has 97 examples in one page.

00:06:01.760 --> 00:06:06.000
So, if you want to know what to do or what it's capable of doing on one page,

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.320
you can do a command F on the site

00:06:08.320 --> 00:06:11.839
and you can most likely find an example that'll be for your needs.

00:06:11.839 --> 00:06:14.239
So, I really want to point that out and say thank you.

00:06:14.239 --> 00:06:16.399
It's something we should all strive for in our packages.

00:06:17.279 --> 00:06:20.640
Again, one month later, GT was released.

00:06:24.720 --> 00:06:30.000
GT is a package that I helped work on a little bit on the infrastructure side.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:33.359
But Rich was mastermind of the whole thing.

00:06:33.359 --> 00:06:35.119
And I think it was one of the first packages

00:06:35.119 --> 00:06:38.959
that took every component of a table

00:06:38.959 --> 00:06:41.440
and treated it as a first-class citizen from the beginning.

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:44.720
Normally, it's just a package that's built

00:06:45.200 --> 00:06:52.079
Normally, it's just our blue summary cells or table's body cells or column label.

00:06:52.079 --> 00:06:54.320
And that's typically what we just land on.

00:06:54.880 --> 00:06:56.239
But Rich said, no, no, no.

00:06:56.239 --> 00:06:59.440
We're going to support anything that a table can support.

00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:01.040
And it's going to be possible from the beginning.

00:07:03.600 --> 00:07:07.679
From that, he can kind of give it the same treatment that ggplot does,

00:07:07.679 --> 00:07:10.000
where you have your structure data at the beginning

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.559
and you may have your pretty formatted plot at the end.

00:07:13.119 --> 00:07:17.200
So with the same idea, he took structured data at the beginning

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:22.640
and he ran formatters on it to finally get your styled table at the end.

00:07:24.320 --> 00:07:28.239
But GT was only done for static plots in mind.

00:07:28.799 --> 00:07:33.679
And in 2023, he added in the ability to do interactive

00:07:34.399 --> 00:07:38.720
by wrapping around the Reactable package, which I thought was great.

00:07:39.839 --> 00:07:42.079
We'll take a limited subset of features,

00:07:42.160 --> 00:07:45.279
but you still have that GT interface with one extra command.

00:07:45.839 --> 00:07:47.200
And I thought that was just awesome.

00:07:48.320 --> 00:07:53.839
This allows us to update the styling and update the API to a gold medal for me.

00:07:54.640 --> 00:07:57.839
And I thought that was just absolutely brilliant and how that worked out.

00:07:59.600 --> 00:08:06.000
Rich, very similar to Reactable, has beautiful examples.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:11.119
I think they're very rich in their design and much deeper than just a toy example.

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:17.519
So please do check out his website and his example datasets and how he uses them.

00:08:22.959 --> 00:08:25.760
In 2023, Shiny for Python was released.

00:08:27.119 --> 00:08:32.080
And about eight months later, like it was at the beginning,

00:08:32.080 --> 00:08:37.200
a little faster, six months later, we added our rendered data frame support.

00:08:38.159 --> 00:08:43.520
And if we kind of look at this timeline, it's a little spooky because there's 10 years

00:08:43.520 --> 00:08:46.960
of experience that Shiny for Python is now having to live up to.

00:08:47.599 --> 00:08:51.760
Yes, there are the other existing widgets that Carson had talked about,

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:53.280
but they're not native.

00:08:53.280 --> 00:08:56.000
There's a little bit of awkwardness to me.

00:08:56.559 --> 00:09:03.359
And so having something native for PyShiny would be an amazing addition to the package.

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:09.440
So it feels like you're just a little toddler and you're living up to your big brother,

00:09:09.440 --> 00:09:15.440
who's got very big shoes to fill, and it's a little daunting.

00:09:16.479 --> 00:09:18.960
So let's check out and see what PyShiny has done.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:27.919
We can quickly see that we have filter support built in per column rather than up top for the

00:09:27.919 --> 00:09:28.640
whole table.

00:09:28.640 --> 00:09:33.599
Given that it's per column, we can actually have context-aware filtering.

00:09:33.599 --> 00:09:39.200
Currently, it's only done for numbers, and everything else is just treated as a text

00:09:39.200 --> 00:09:39.760
subset.

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:45.599
So in the country, I will search for stat, and we will filter down to the United States,

00:09:46.719 --> 00:09:47.919
and that's updated live.

00:09:49.440 --> 00:09:56.000
And for population, because it's numeric, we have the ability to do a minimum of one

00:09:56.559 --> 00:09:59.359
and we have the ability to do a minimum and maximum.

00:09:59.359 --> 00:10:03.599
And I just kept entering a number in the minimum until the data was shortened up.

00:10:05.679 --> 00:10:07.119
Oh, sorry, I didn't mention it.

00:10:08.239 --> 00:10:13.840
This is a toy example, looking at the gap-minder values per country, maximum values.

00:10:13.840 --> 00:10:17.599
And so there's population, life expectancy, and the GDP per capita.

00:10:18.400 --> 00:10:26.479
And what we can also do is we can style these tables.

00:10:27.599 --> 00:10:30.159
So it's kind of a little hint as to what's going on.

00:10:31.679 --> 00:10:35.919
Granted, we can sort and filter on the columns, we can select our rows, and then we can, in

00:10:35.919 --> 00:10:41.840
addition, we can get that selected data out of the render.

00:10:41.840 --> 00:10:46.000
I'll go into this a little bit more in detail, but that transition of getting that selected

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.320
data is very, very slow now.

00:10:51.280 --> 00:10:59.520
You can see here as well that the columns have highlighted their top five values in

00:10:59.520 --> 00:11:00.559
each column.

00:11:00.559 --> 00:11:06.159
So in the case of GDP per capita, it's green, life expectancy I put blue, and population

00:11:06.159 --> 00:11:06.640
was red.

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:13.840
Kuwait has a very high max value for the GDP per capita, so to show off the editing values,

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:17.520
I'm just going to change the value by removing the leading one from the number.

00:11:18.559 --> 00:11:27.039
And hopefully the top five values within the GDP per capita will be readjusted to the new

00:11:27.039 --> 00:11:27.919
top five values.

00:11:28.479 --> 00:11:31.840
So in this case, China will get their value to be selected as green.

00:11:33.280 --> 00:11:38.719
So we delete the one, and then the styling, because there's been a new edited value, we

00:11:38.719 --> 00:11:42.960
can then have the Python code recalculate what style should be applied, and it's sent

00:11:42.960 --> 00:11:43.599
to the browser.

00:11:44.640 --> 00:11:48.640
So we don't have to have everything in the browser, because I think we're more effective

00:11:48.640 --> 00:11:50.880
as, in this case, writing Python ourselves.

00:11:55.280 --> 00:12:01.359
So putting up our table of Olympic medals, DT, our Hanson table, Reactable, they all

00:12:01.359 --> 00:12:07.520
have their own strengths, and then GT improves upon the styling and API on top of Reactable.

00:12:08.799 --> 00:12:10.320
And Shiny for Python.

00:12:11.039 --> 00:12:12.000
It's not perfect.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:12.719
We're getting there.

00:12:13.280 --> 00:12:14.960
Filtering, I think, is improved.

00:12:14.960 --> 00:12:16.719
We have some context to where in the columns.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
Styling is on the Python side.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:23.200
We can give some JSON that goes to where it needs to go.

00:12:24.479 --> 00:12:26.239
API is quite small.

00:12:26.239 --> 00:12:28.159
We don't have it cover all the options yet.

00:12:28.159 --> 00:12:32.159
I know this, but we're adding options as we see fit.

00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:37.599
The speed is similar to how Reactable is done, very fast with the virtualized DOM.

00:12:38.400 --> 00:12:46.000
So I do want to toot our own horn there, because it is really impressive as to how that virtual

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:46.960
DOM works.

00:12:47.840 --> 00:12:51.840
And then editing, our Hanson table is something to strive for.

00:12:51.840 --> 00:12:57.679
We have one more cycle coming up, and I'm aware of the contexts in the browser, so hopefully

00:12:57.679 --> 00:13:01.760
we can get something in there and use our Shiny inputs that we already have.

00:13:01.760 --> 00:13:06.799
So, empowered render, this is something that I want to get into, because I think it's really

00:13:06.799 --> 00:13:09.760
exciting on the Python side that we can leverage class structures.

00:13:11.520 --> 00:13:17.119
And this is where we take a renderer object and we can add in extra reactive values and

00:13:17.119 --> 00:13:19.039
methods to this renderer object.

00:13:19.840 --> 00:13:25.760
And this is a very exciting advancement in, like, the style of coding done within Shiny

00:13:25.760 --> 00:13:26.320
for Python.

00:13:26.320 --> 00:13:33.280
So let's look at the reactive graph of some made-up example, and this is using an artistic

00:13:33.280 --> 00:13:36.400
form of the React, R's React log graph.

00:13:37.200 --> 00:13:43.679
So if you are an R user and you want to see how Shiny thinks about your reactivity, please

00:13:43.679 --> 00:13:45.280
check out the React log package.

00:13:45.280 --> 00:13:48.880
I know I'm talking about Shiny for Python right now, but please do check it out.

00:13:48.880 --> 00:13:50.000
I'm a little biased.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:58.559
So let's say that there is a data frame in your final output there, and for an input,

00:13:58.559 --> 00:14:02.640
I want to look at the sort information of that data frame.

00:14:02.640 --> 00:14:04.400
Normally, this is done from the browser.

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:08.479
We set an input value and it comes back to Shiny, and Shiny has it available as an input.

00:14:09.520 --> 00:14:15.280
However, how does this data frame connect to the output?

00:14:15.599 --> 00:14:21.200
However, how does this data frame connect to that input?

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:27.440
It's kind of magical, it's kind of voodoo for me, but it just shows up and it's untyped

00:14:27.440 --> 00:14:29.280
and, you know, best of luck understanding it.

00:14:30.960 --> 00:14:36.000
Instead, what we can do with the empowered renderer is add these methods, and it kind

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:40.719
of allows us to rearrange that reactive graph so that we can add a method of sort, so that

00:14:40.719 --> 00:14:44.799
you can access the sort information of your renderer.

00:14:44.799 --> 00:14:49.119
It'll have autocomplete, it'll have typing, you know, that is just awesome.

00:14:52.640 --> 00:14:58.320
So, for example, for the data frame, we have typed data objects, such as the data that

00:14:58.320 --> 00:15:02.719
the user provided to your render function, like the iris data frame.

00:15:03.359 --> 00:15:09.440
We have data view, which would be how is the user currently filtered or sorting in the

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:10.080
columns?

00:15:10.080 --> 00:15:11.679
What does that look like to the user?

00:15:12.239 --> 00:15:15.200
That way you can take it and replicate it in a follow-up table if you'd like.

00:15:17.440 --> 00:15:23.840
You can have multiple input objects, such as what is the user selected for their cells?

00:15:24.479 --> 00:15:26.000
What filters have they applied?

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:27.599
What sorting have they applied?

00:15:27.599 --> 00:15:30.719
And anything else that we can try to think of, we can add these there.

00:15:31.760 --> 00:15:34.479
And similarly, we can have update methods.

00:15:34.479 --> 00:15:40.239
So rather than going to try to find the corresponding update method that isn't attached and just

00:15:40.239 --> 00:15:45.840
kind of works with what you're doing, it's now fully integrated into your renderer object.

00:15:51.760 --> 00:15:56.799
Historically, we've always supported pandas, because it just kind of got us off the ground,

00:15:56.799 --> 00:15:58.000
ready to go for our examples.

00:15:58.880 --> 00:16:01.119
But, you know, Shiny needs to be generic.

00:16:01.119 --> 00:16:06.000
We shouldn't have predetermined a choice on what data frame to use.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:11.679
So in the Shiny 1.0 release, we added in native polar support to try to help expand

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:16.239
our data frame support for the package.

00:16:17.119 --> 00:16:21.919
But what I'm really excited about with this is we're adding narwhals support in the next

00:16:21.919 --> 00:16:22.640
release.

00:16:22.640 --> 00:16:28.479
And narwhals is a really good compatibility layer between data frame libraries.

00:16:29.440 --> 00:16:33.119
And it handles all of the complicated mess for us.

00:16:33.760 --> 00:16:38.559
So we can just take in the data frame that we don't know necessarily how to handle.

00:16:39.200 --> 00:16:43.599
We tell narwhals, please select these columns and these rows, and then give me the native

00:16:43.599 --> 00:16:44.320
data frame back.

00:16:45.039 --> 00:16:46.799
And it's handled for us.

00:16:46.799 --> 00:16:48.880
And I think that's such a beautiful solution.

00:16:48.880 --> 00:16:51.840
And as they get better, Shiny will get better as well.

00:16:51.840 --> 00:17:00.400
So looking into the future, Great Tables is obviously out for Python, and we need support

00:17:00.400 --> 00:17:01.440
for this within Shiny.

00:17:01.440 --> 00:17:03.440
I think it's just such a wonderful package.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:09.439
And we need to have the support because they know the original data and they know the formatted

00:17:09.439 --> 00:17:10.000
data.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:15.359
That makes a really nice editable experience that we can just update a cell, have it reformatted,

00:17:15.359 --> 00:17:17.119
and then we send it back to the browser.

00:17:17.119 --> 00:17:21.920
And styling is really amazing in how easy it is to do within Great Tables.

00:17:23.199 --> 00:17:27.040
In addition to this, Reactable for Python has just been ported over.

00:17:28.160 --> 00:17:31.520
And this is a great thanks to both of these packages to Michael Chow.

00:17:33.520 --> 00:17:37.040
And so it's kind of up in the air as to what's going to happen.

00:17:37.680 --> 00:17:41.520
But we could possibly port our cell editing into Reactable.

00:17:42.319 --> 00:17:44.560
We could possibly port our data into Reactable.

00:17:45.520 --> 00:17:50.479
We could possibly integrate Great Tables into Reactable, similar to how we did on the R side.

00:17:51.680 --> 00:17:55.760
Who knows as to what will happen, but it'll be coming up in our discussions.

